## Tone and Style Patterns — Distilled

### Openings that work (use these patterns)
| Pattern | Example |
|---|---|
| Analogy hook | "You wouldn't hire a brand-new SRE to lead a critical outage on day one. So why do we assume generic AI can?" |
| Contrarian statement | "The next competitive advantage in AI isn't about what models know. It's about what your organization can *do*." |
| Problem statement | "Getting disaster recovery runbooks off a spreadsheet and into production takes weeks. It shouldn't." |
| Industry assumption flip | "Everyone is talking about AI training data. We think they're asking the wrong question." |

### Closings that work
- End with a forward-looking vision, not a summary
- The last sentence should leave the reader feeling something — aspiration, urgency, or clarity
- Examples:
  - *"Done right, this means fewer outages and faster recovery. And that is a vision of resilience worth chasing."*
  - *"We don't just help you adopt AI — we help you control it."*
  - *"The gap between intent and execution is where outages live. Cutover closes it."*

### Things these examples never do
- Never open with "In today's fast-paced world..."
- Never use passive voice for key claims
- Never save the main point for the end — lead with it
- Never describe Cutover as a "project management" or "workflow" tool
- Never use corporate buzzwords: "synergy," "leverage" (as a verb), "circle back," "touch base"
- Never make a claim without grounding it in a real scenario or proof point

